    <a title="Liz Janet" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5114433-liz-janet"><img alt="Liz Janet" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1574021381p2/5114433.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1454456558?book_show_action=true">Nov 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Liz Janet" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Liz Janet" href="/user/show/5114433-liz-janet">Liz Janet</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5114433-liz-janet?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1454456558" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16802618686728273775"><i>“It isn&apos;t about being or not being dead, it&apos;s about what you leave behind.”</i><br/><br/>This is not just a story of a writer in a totalitarian police state whose gruesome stories are happening. Nor is it about different forms of interrogation nor censorship. Nor is it solely on the responsibility of the author after his stories are being acted out in gruesome ways. This is a story of a writer becoming obsessed, while going interrogation, with having his stories survive his punishment. <br/><br/>The best part of the pl</span>
  <span id="freeText16802618686728273775" style="display:none"><i>“It isn't about being or not being dead, it's about what you leave behind.”</i><br><br>This is not just a story of a writer in a totalitarian police state whose gruesome stories are happening. Nor is it about different forms of interrogation nor censorship. Nor is it solely on the responsibility of the author after his stories are being acted out in gruesome ways. This is a story of a writer becoming obsessed, while going interrogation, with having his stories survive his punishment. <br><br>The best part of the play, to me at least, was the short stories by the writer told throughout the play. My favourite was "The Three Gibbet Crossroads," since I am still unable to see what could be worse than rape and murder within the context. Another brilliant one was "The Tale of the Town on the River," this is how re-tellings should be done all the time. "The Pillowman" makes me depressed, but I love it too much. And lastly "The Writer and the Writer's Brother," if this were a true story I would have cried even more than I did while reading it. <br><br><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/11/theater/reviews/a-storytelling-instinct-revels-in-horrors-fun.html?_r=0" rel="nofollow noopener">A Storytelling Instinct Revels in Horror's Fun</a><br><br>I wish I had read this play sooner, because it is brilliant, and now I wished I had seen the dramatization with David Tennant and Jim Broadbent. I will read this many times over, I guarantee it. <br>PLEASE READ IT! IT IS BRILLIANT AND GREAT AND JUST AWESOME!<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1429793525ra/14630758.gif" width="500" height="200" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br></span>
