        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer746682020" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6365975912097150965">This play is amazing. I just read some of the other reviews, and &quot;devastating&quot; is a word that also rings true. It is so horrific, and yet so funny, that the guilt you feel when you snigger is overwhelming. Again, reflecting another review, some plays don&apos;t read well - this one does. And yet, I can also visualise it on stage. But wonder whether some sort of age limit should be given! I was reading it with a view to assessing the proposal that our amateur dramatics group should put it on. While we</span>
  <span id="freeText6365975912097150965" style="display:none">This play is amazing. I just read some of the other reviews, and "devastating" is a word that also rings true. It is so horrific, and yet so funny, that the guilt you feel when you snigger is overwhelming. Again, reflecting another review, some plays don't read well - this one does. And yet, I can also visualise it on stage. But wonder whether some sort of age limit should be given! I was reading it with a view to assessing the proposal that our amateur dramatics group should put it on. While we undertake to put on "Plays of Merit", and don't say anything about taste, there is an element of impropriety about this play that makes me wonder if we'd get thrown out of the theatre. It's dark, very dark, and yet... surely this sort of play should be performed? It can't be ignored because it isn't very nice... or can it?<br /><br />The play is about a storyteller, and some of his stories, including the title story, are related over the play (although told, rather than acted out). It might seem odd, but I can imagine this working. <br /><br />This gets 5 stars for blowing my shoes off.<br /><br />**edit: our company did take this play forward. the audiences enjoyed it a lot, and the local church even gave a sermon ABOUT it, which was something else. (note: spoilers in Canon Black's sermon! <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://canonianblack.wordpress.com/2017/04/09/the-pillowman-and-the-passion/">https://canonianblack.wordpress.com/2...</a>) <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6365975912097150965" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


