<div id="review_846970061" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/846970061" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1018916-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1216934475p2/1018916.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/846970061?book_show_action=true">Feb 06, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/1018916-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer846970061" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer619782416840878668">I have heard talk of The Pillowman for years. Ok, not talk. Whispers. This play seems shrouded in mystery and myth. I have not seen the play performed, and after reading it, I&apos;m not sure if I want to. The scenes are very intense, but also, there is quite a good bit of storytelling going on here, which is conducive to reading. I find it amazing that McDonagh not only conjured up this brilliant play, but also the brilliant dark fairy tales that are told within it. It is so effective though.<br/><br/>While r</span>
  <span id="freeText619782416840878668" style="display:none">I have heard talk of The Pillowman for years. Ok, not talk. Whispers. This play seems shrouded in mystery and myth. I have not seen the play performed, and after reading it, I'm not sure if I want to. The scenes are very intense, but also, there is quite a good bit of storytelling going on here, which is conducive to reading. I find it amazing that McDonagh not only conjured up this brilliant play, but also the brilliant dark fairy tales that are told within it. It is so effective though.<br /><br />While reading the play, I couldn't help but see Kafka permeating the tone, setting, and characters. The interrogation style also reminded me of Pinter's The Birthday Party. Something sinister runs through the entire play, whether it is from a character, a story, or the world in which they live. The play takes place in a police station, either in an interrogation room or a cell. The main character, Katurian Katurian Katurian (echoes of The Trial's K) is detained by two police on suspicion of killing three little children, who all were killed in accordance with methods he details in three dark fairy tales he wrote. The rest of his work is now being investigated, and therefore his character along with it. He only ever wrote one "nice" story, and it is the one his brother, Michal, fixates on. Michal is brought in for questioning, as the police believe he will give up Katurian for the crimes. Michal has mental problems, and so make an easy target for the police - or so they think. <br /><br />There is so much misdirection in this play that McDonagh must have been a magician in a past life. While some of the subject matter is reprehensible and disturbing, he still finds a way to bring out the humanness in each of the characters. I was transfixed by the writing, the story and the characters that I read it in one sitting on one of the coldest days of the year. It sure made the time go by quickly. For anyone who thinks stage plays are boring or outdated should definitely read or see this one.</span>
  <a data-text-id="619782416840878668" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


