<div id="review_463718992" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/463718992" />
    <a title="Kat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1008175-kat"><img alt="Kat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370231937p2/1008175.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/463718992?book_show_action=true">Nov 25, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kat" href="/user/show/1008175-kat">Kat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1008175-kat?shelf=2013">2013</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1008175-kat?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer463718992" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13323836271704904040">Basic Plot: Katurian wrote short stories that inspired several child murders, so now he&apos;s been taken by police in a totalitarian state who are attempting to discover the truth.<br/><br/>This was one intense play. The whole thing is essentially a police interrogation. We are never told where it is, though with the author being Irish there are some distinctly UK-type slang expressions used. It&apos;s not terribly specific, though, so it really could take place anywhere. The names are also varied in culture, so t</span>
  <span id="freeText13323836271704904040" style="display:none">Basic Plot: Katurian wrote short stories that inspired several child murders, so now he's been taken by police in a totalitarian state who are attempting to discover the truth.<br /><br />This was one intense play. The whole thing is essentially a police interrogation. We are never told where it is, though with the author being Irish there are some distinctly UK-type slang expressions used. It's not terribly specific, though, so it really could take place anywhere. The names are also varied in culture, so they don't make the place specific, either.<br /><br />The plot brings to mind a lot of themes associated with dystopian societies, particularly in the idea of who should be punished for what a storyteller writes. The writer, or the person who acts on the writing? The writer, or the person who misinterprets the meaning of the writing? There are a lot of questions in there. It's thought-provoking.<br /><br />I can see why the play won the Olivier award. The writing really does make the play, and I was able to vividly picture every character and scene as I read the dialogue. There is language and violence in it, so it's not exactly good fodder for a high school drama club, but some of the scenes would make great exercises for an acting class.<br /><br />Overall, an excellent play and an excellent read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13323836271704904040" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


